         <abstract>
            <p>The papers of the firm of Almy and Brown.--The firm's business prosperous in 1801-1807, 675.--The Embargo dealt a heavy blow, 677.--Yet many new mills built in 1808-1809, 681.--The practice of price-maintenance suggested as an explanation of the growth, 682.--New markets in the West and South after the Embargo, 686.--Conclusions, 688.</p>
